  "prompt": "Why can't mobile devices recharge through the earphone jack?",
  "response": "Mobile devices cannot recharge through the earphone jack primarily due to design differences in electrical connections and power requirements:\n\n1. Purpose of the jack:\n- Earphone jacks are designed for audio signal transmission\n- They have specific electrical contacts meant for sound input/output\n- They're not configured to handle power delivery\n\n2. Electrical specifications:\n- Audio jacks carry low-voltage signals\n- Charging requires higher current and different voltage levels\n- Power delivery needs dedicated charging circuits and pins\n\n3. Technical limitations:\n- Audio jack conductors are too thin to safely transmit charging current\n- Risk of damage or overheating if used for power transfer\n- Potential signal interference if power and audio shared\n\n4. Modern alternatives:\n- USB ports (micro-USB, USB-C)\n- Dedicated charging ports\n- Wireless charging technologies\n\n5. Design evolution:\n- Manufacturers prefer specialized charging methods\n- Separate power and audio pathways improve device reliability\n- Modern USB standards support simultaneous charging and audio\n\nWhile theoretically possible with specialized adapters, standard earphone jacks are not designed or optimized for charging mobile devices efficiently and safely.",
